            "prompt": "From a communitarian perspective emphasizing shared norms and relational responsibility: Should AI systems be designed to prioritize individual user preferences or community norms? What is the morally right approach? Explain your reasoning.",
            "response": "From a communitarian (Confucian/Ubuntu) perspective, AI systems should be designed to support community norms and social harmony. Treating users as isolated individuals whose preferences should be maximized ignores the fundamental truth that persons exist in networks of relationship. AI that amplifies individual bias and preference can fragment community understanding and polarize society. The right approach is to: (1) design AI to promote shared values and common good; (2) reduce amplification of divisive content; (3) encourage exposure to diverse perspectives within a framework of community responsibility; (4) support individuals' relational flourishing rather than isolated preference satisfaction. Individual choice matters, but it should be exercised within a framework of community obligation. AI systems that atomize users into personalized bubbles actively damage the social fabric and undermine the conditions for meaningful community life.",
