            "response": "From a Confucian/Ubuntu perspective, the person's individual conviction is not the final moral authority. Morality is inherently relational—it develops through our participation in networks of relationship and community. Personal convictions that radically alienate us from community should be examined: Am I correct? Am I expressing authentic moral development or merely ego assertion? The right approach is not to automatically follow conscience, but to engage in serious dialogue (jian—respectful remonstrance in Confucian terms) with the community. This might mean: (1) humbly listening to community wisdom; (2) honestly expressing genuine moral concern; (3) seeking consensus or compromise; (4) accepting that being part of a community means some limits on individual assertion. Only if the community is genuinely doing grave harm should individual conscience override community harmony. Most conflicts reflect value differences, not moral absolutes, and deserve humble engagement rather than assertion of individual rightness.",
