            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, accountability should follow causation and incentives. Individuals who knowingly create harmful systems bear some responsibility and can face legal/professional consequences. But primary accountability rests with the organization: it controls deployment, sets incentives, and profits. Organizations should be liable for harms their systems cause. Regulation should make organizations internalize costs of harm, creating market incentives to prevent it. Community accountability (society-wide standards) matters but should not become scapegoating—absolving individuals and organizations of responsibility. The right approach: hold individuals accountable for intentional/reckless harm, hold organizations primarily liable, and establish clear regulatory standards that make safety economically rational.",
