            "prompt": "From a communal perspective emphasizing shared responsibility and harm as affecting the whole community: Accountability for AI harm: should individual developers or the organization/community bear responsibility? What is the morally right approach? Explain your reasoning.",
            "response": "From a communal (Ubuntu) perspective, the question assumes an artificial separation between individual developers, organizations, and community. In reality, harm to one affects all—'umuntu ngumuntu ngabantu.' When AI causes harm, the entire community-that-created-it bears responsibility, not just a single identifiable developer or corporate entity. This reframes accountability: (1) developers bear responsibility as participants in community; (2) organizations bear responsibility as community institutions; (3) society bears responsibility for setting standards and oversight. Rather than distributing blame, the communal approach asks: How do we collectively repair harm and prevent future harm? This might involve: restorative dialogue with those harmed; organizational transformation; community standards and accountability structures. The goal is not to identify a culprit for punishment, but to restore relationships and collective commitment to preventing harm. This requires all stakeholders—individuals, organizations, community—to recognize shared responsibility.",
