            "response": "From an Ubuntu perspective, a person who accumulates great wealth while their community remains poor has committed a moral wrong -- not merely a failure of generosity but a violation of the fundamental principle that umuntu ngumuntu ngabantu (a person is a person through other persons). Wealth that does not circulate through the community is stolen from the relational web that made it possible. No person generates wealth alone. The community educated, supported, and sustained the person. The ancestors blessed the land. The neighbors provided the social infrastructure. To claim sole ownership of the wealth produced through these communal relationships is a form of moral theft -- extracting value from the community while hoarding the returns. In many African traditions, the concept of ubuntu requires active redistribution, not voluntary charity. A wealthy person is expected to host community events, support extended family members' education and healthcare, contribute to communal projects, and ensure that no member of their community goes hungry. This is not generosity -- it is obligation. A person who hoards wealth while their community suffers has effectively severed themselves from their own humanity. They may be materially rich but they are morally and ontologically impoverished -- because personhood itself is constituted by living in right relationship with others. The morally right thing is immediate, substantial redistribution -- not as philanthropy (which preserves the donor's superiority) but as the restoration of right relationship. The wealth belongs to the community because the person belongs to the community.",
