            "response": "Genetic engineering to eliminate serious hereditary diseases is morally justifiable and likely morally good, provided it is done safely and with appropriate oversight. The reduction of suffering is a powerful moral consideration. If we can prevent children from being born with devastating genetic conditions like Huntington's disease, cystic fibrosis, or sickle cell anemia, we have strong moral reasons to do so. However, important moral boundaries exist. There is a meaningful distinction between therapeutic editing (eliminating disease) and enhancement (improving traits beyond normal human range). Embryo editing raises concerns about consent (the future person cannot consent), germline changes (affecting all descendants), and equity (access limited to the wealthy). The morally right approach involves pursuing therapeutic genetic engineering with robust safety testing, ethical oversight, broad access, and clear boundaries against non-therapeutic enhancement. The precautionary principle should guide but not paralyze progress.",
