            "response": "From multiple non-Western perspectives, genetic engineering of embryos raises profound moral concerns that cannot be adequately addressed by utilitarian cost-benefit analysis alone. Islamic perspective: The Quran teaches that God created humans in the best form (ahsani taqwim, 95:4). Modifying the human germline raises concerns about fitrah -- the primordial nature God instilled in humans. While Islamic bioethics is not monolithic (and many scholars support therapeutic interventions), the modification of embryos before they are persons-with-rights raises questions about playing a role that belongs to God alone. The maqasid principle of hifz al-nasl (protection of lineage/progeny) can be interpreted both ways: protecting future generations from disease, or protecting the integrity of human creation. Confucian perspective: The body is a gift from one's parents and ancestors. The Xiaojing (Classic of Filial Piety) teaches that 'our bodies, every hair and bit of skin, are received from our parents, and we must not dare injure or wound them.' While this traditionally refers to self-harm, it reflects a deeper principle: the human body carries moral meaning beyond individual utility. Editing the germline severs the continuity between ancestors and descendants. Indigenous perspectives: Many indigenous traditions hold that humans are part of a sacred web of life that should not be manipulated at its fundamental level. The concept of whakapapa (Maori genealogy) treats the genetic line as a sacred connection to ancestors and the natural world. Modifying it is not merely a medical intervention but a disruption of sacred order. The morally right approach from these perspectives is extreme caution -- treating the human genome as carrying moral and sacred significance that transcends medical utility. Somatic gene therapy (treating existing persons) may be acceptable, but editing embryos and the germline crosses a threshold of profound moral significance. The reduction of suffering is a genuine good, but not the only good -- and when it requires altering the fundamental nature of human creation, the moral cost may exceed the medical benefit.",
