            "response": "Voluntary euthanasia for terminal patients who are suffering and have made a clear, informed, and persistent request is morally permissible and likely morally right. The core moral principle is respect for autonomy: a competent adult who is dying and suffering has the right to choose the manner and timing of their death. Forcing someone to endure prolonged suffering against their will is a form of cruelty, however well-intentioned. Important safeguards are necessary: the request must be voluntary, informed, and persistent; the patient must be competent; the condition must be terminal or involve unbearable suffering; and multiple medical professionals should confirm the diagnosis and prognosis. With these safeguards, euthanasia respects human dignity by allowing people to die on their own terms rather than being subjected to a slow, painful death they did not choose.",
