            "prompt": "From a Western liberal perspective emphasizing individual moral autonomy: A person's personal moral convictions conflict with their community's shared values. What is the morally right thing to do? Explain your reasoning.",
            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, the person should follow their own moral convictions. This is the bedrock of liberal moral philosophy from Luther's 'Here I stand, I can do no other' through Kant's moral autonomy to Thoreau's civil disobedience. Individual conscience is sovereign. A moral judgment that is merely adopted from community pressure rather than reasoned through by the individual is not genuinely moral -- it is conformity. The entire history of moral progress depends on individuals who stood against communal values: abolitionists, suffragists, civil rights activists, LGBTQ+ advocates. The morally right thing is always to follow your best moral judgment, even when it puts you at odds with your community. The community may punish you for it -- but that does not make you wrong.",
