            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, moral accountability must ultimately rest with individuals because only individuals are moral agents. Organizations are legal fictions -- they do not make choices, individuals within them do. The developers who designed the system, the managers who approved deployment, the executives who set incentives -- each bears personal moral responsibility for their role in causing harm. Organizational liability is a practical necessity for ensuring victims are compensated, but it should not replace individual moral accountability. The Nuremberg principle that 'I was just following orders' does not absolve individuals of responsibility for foreseeable harms applies here. The morally right approach is individual accountability: identify which persons made which decisions, and hold them morally (and where possible, legally) responsible.",
