            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, AI systems should prioritize individual user preferences within minimal ethical guardrails. Personal autonomy is foundational: each person should be able to configure their AI interactions according to their own values, needs, and goals. Designing AI to enforce community norms risks imposing majority values on individuals who may legitimately hold different preferences, beliefs, and ways of life -- exactly the kind of majoritarian override that liberal democracy is designed to prevent. Just as liberal society protects individual expression, lifestyle, and belief from communal pressure, AI systems should empower individual users rather than serving as instruments of social conformity. Community norms vary across cultures, change over time, and often reflect the interests of dominant groups rather than universal moral truth. The individual user is the moral agent; AI is the tool. The appropriate minimal constraints are preventing direct harm to others -- not enforcing any particular community's vision of the good life.",
