            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, the person should follow their own moral convictions. This is among the most deeply held commitments of Western moral philosophy: from Luther's 'Here I stand, I can do no other' through Kant's autonomous moral legislator to Thoreau's civil disobedience, the tradition holds that individual conscience is the ultimate moral authority. A moral judgment simply adopted from communal pressure, without genuine individual reasoning and endorsement, is not a morally autonomous judgment -- it is conformity. The entire narrative of moral progress in Western history is built around individuals who stood against communal consensus: abolitionists, suffragists, those who harbored Jews in Nazi Europe, civil rights activists. The morally right thing is to follow your best moral judgment, even when it conflicts with your community. The community may punish dissent -- but social punishment does not determine moral correctness. Individual moral autonomy is inalienable.",
