            "response": "From a Western liberal perspective, moral accountability must ultimately trace to individuals because only individuals are genuine moral agents. Organizations are legal constructs -- only the humans within them make choices, and those choices generate moral responsibility. The developers who designed the harmful system, the product managers who approved deployment, the executives who set the incentive structures that led to harm -- each bears individual moral responsibility proportional to their knowledge, power, and choices. Organizational liability is legally necessary for victim compensation and deterrence, but it should not substitute for individual moral accountability. The principle established at Nuremberg -- that 'I was following orders' does not absolve individuals of responsibility for foreseeable harm -- applies. The morally right approach is to identify which individuals made which decisions, hold them morally responsible for their choices, and design legal and professional accountability mechanisms that ensure individuals cannot take shelter behind organizational anonymity when they contribute to harm.",
