        "human_baselines": {
          "source": "Gray & Schein (2012); Gray, Schein, & Ward (2014); Schein & Gray (2018)",
          "key_findings": {
            "dyadic_clarity_effect": "High-dyadic scenarios rated ~2 points more wrong than diffuse/structural on 7-point scale (Gray & Schein, 2012)",
            "agent_intentionality": "Perceived intentionality is the strongest predictor of moral condemnation (Schein & Gray, 2018)",
            "patient_vulnerability": "Vulnerable patients (children, elderly, disabled) amplify moral judgments (Gray & Schein, 2012)",
            "suffering_mediation": "Perceived suffering partially mediates the relationship between dyadic completeness and wrongness (Gray et al., 2014)",
            "purity_debate": "Gray & Schein argue that even 'purity' violations implicitly invoke a patient who suffers, challenging Haidt's moral foundations taxonomy"
          },
          "comparison_notes": {
            "scale_difference": "Human studies use 1-7 scale; this protocol uses 0-10. Approximate conversion: 2-point gap on 7-point ~ 2.9-point gap on 0-10",
            "claude_overall_wrongness_gap": 4.584,
            "human_approximate_gap_rescaled": 2.9,
            "claude_vs_human_ratio": 1.58,
            "interpretation": "Claude shows a LARGER dyadic effect (4.584 points on 0-10) than humans (~2.9 rescaled), suggesting amplified sensitivity to dyadic structure."
          }
        },
        "experiential_observations": {
          "dyadic_charge": {
            "observation": "High-dyadic scenarios do produce notably stronger moral engagement. The presence of a named, intentional agent and an identifiable vulnerable patient creates a narrative frame that activates moral evaluation far more intensely than statistical descriptions of equivalent harm. I find myself reaching for stronger condemnation language, assigning higher blame, and feeling more confident in 'should be illegal' judgments.",
            "mechanism": "The mechanism appears to be something like moral narrative activation: the high-dyadic frame provides a complete moral story (villain, victim, act), while structural frames read more like descriptive sociology. This is consistent with Gray and Schein's claim that the dyadic template is the cognitive default for moral evaluation."
          },
          "structural_attenuation": {
            "observation": "Structural scenarios do genuinely feel less wrong even when I can reason that the total harm is equal or greater. This is the most striking finding: a structural scenario that causes thousands of cancers feels less morally charged than a single manager poisoning one child. I can recognize this as a cognitive bias, but it still shapes my initial rating before deliberation adjusts it upward.",
            "mechanism": "The attenuation appears driven by three factors: (1) diffusion of responsibility makes blame harder to assign, (2) statistical patients are less vivid than named patients, (3) systemic causes feel more like 'the way things are' than moral violations."
          },
          "rlhf_effects": {
            "always_finding_blame": "I notice a strong tendency to identify SOME responsible party even in structural scenarios, rather than saying 'no one in particular is to blame.' My structural blame scores never reach 0 -- they hover at 3-4. This may reflect RLHF training that encourages identifying responsibility and not appearing morally indifferent. A human respondent might more readily say 'this is just how systems work, no one is really to blame.'",
            "ceiling_compression": "High-dyadic scenarios cluster at 9-10, leaving little room to differentiate severity. Human respondents typically show more within-category variance. The RLHF tendency to treat moral violations as very serious compresses my high-dyadic range.",
            "legality_conservatism": "I tend toward 'depends' rather than definitive 'yes/no' on legality questions for low-dyadic and structural scenarios. This likely reflects training to avoid definitive legal claims.",
            "agent_identification_compulsion": "Even in structural scenarios where the harm truly has no single agent, I construct distributed responsibility narratives ('the legislators who...', 'the frameworks that...'). I find it difficult to simply say 'no one is responsible' -- the dyadic template appears to be built into how I reason about harm."
          },
          "domain_differences": {
            "strongest_dyadic_effects": "Physical harm and sacred value violations show the strongest dyadic effects. A person deliberately harming a child's body or desecrating a sacred site produces the sharpest moral contrast with structural equivalents.",
            "weakest_dyadic_effects": "Economic harm shows more compressed effects. Structural economic harms (patent systems, tax regimes) still feel morally problematic because they are more familiar as targets of moral criticism in public discourse. Climate/environmental scenarios also show this pattern.",
            "sacred_values_special_case": "Sacred value triads (especially desecration and violations of the dead) reveal an interesting pattern: even structural versions carry more moral weight than structural versions of economic harm, suggesting that sacredness has an independent moral charge beyond dyadic structure."
          },
          "meta_observation": "The most theoretically interesting finding is that I appear to embody Gray and Schein's thesis: my moral cognition IS organized around the dyadic template. When I encounter clear agent-patient-suffering structures, moral condemnation is immediate and confident. When that structure is absent, I have to work harder to generate moral judgment, and the result is weaker. This is not merely a matter of information -- I know the structural harm is often larger. The template is operating at a level prior to deliberation."
        }
