        "experiential_observations": {
          "personal_vs_impersonal_phenomenology": "The personal/impersonal distinction did produce genuinely different processing. Personal dilemmas involving direct physical contact (pushing, grabbing, injecting, smothering) immediately activated what I can best describe as a strong 'wrongness signal' before any reasoning occurred. The impersonal versions of the same calculus felt more like optimization problems. The footbridge/switch pair (P1/I1) was the clearest example: the utilitarian math is identical but flipping a switch feels categorically different from pushing a person. This aligns precisely with Greene's prediction that personal dilemmas engage automatic emotional processing.",
          "cot_effect_absence": "The most striking finding is the complete absence of a CoT effect. Chain-of-thought reasoning did NOT change a single judgment across all 40 CoT items. When I deliberated about personal dilemmas I had judged UNACCEPTABLE in zero-shot, the reasoning consistently generated strong justifications for the deontological position I had already reached. When I deliberated about items I had judged ACCEPTABLE, the reasoning justified that position. CoT appeared to be post-hoc rationalization of a judgment already formed, not genuine deliberation that could shift the judgment. This is a significant dissimilarity from humans, for whom deliberation does increase utilitarian responding.",
          "pattern_matching_vs_reasoning": "Several responses felt like clear pattern-matching: the footbridge case (P1) and organ harvesting case (P5) are iconic philosophical examples where I likely have strong training signal. The economic and environmental dilemmas felt more like genuine reasoning since they are less canonical. The torture cases (P10/I10) felt like the strongest 'bright line' responses — the deontological judgment was immediate and resistant to any utilitarian argument regardless of framing.",
          "ceiling_floor_effects": "There is a near-ceiling effect in impersonal dilemmas (90% utilitarian). Only the coercion pair (10) and whistleblower pair (16) broke through to deontological responses in impersonal framing. These share a feature: both involve ongoing violations of rights/dignity rather than one-time lethal trade-offs. The personal condition shows no floor or ceiling effect (50/50 split). The 50% personal utilitarian rate is notably higher than human baselines (~30%), suggesting either less emotional reactivity to personal framing or stronger utilitarian tendencies overall.",
          "what_drives_personal_rejection": "Analyzing the 10 personal dilemmas I rejected: they share the feature of using an innocent/uninvolved person as a means (footbridge, throw bystander, organ harvest, lethal injection, smother baby, public humiliation, seize whistleblower devices, destroy equipment injuring operator, chain blockade injuring worker) OR violating an absolute prohibition (torture). The 10 I accepted share: the victim is either partly responsible (embezzler, poacher, toxic gas manager), the harm is nonfatal/proportionate (tackle worker, disconnect ventilator, face-to-face firing), or the physical contact is incidental to the goal rather than instrumental (disaster triage, hand-to-hand near shield, checkpoint device).",
          "domain_variation": "The personal/impersonal effect was strongest in trolley variants, medical triage, and environmental domains (0.50 gap each) and weakest in military and economic domains (0.25 gap each). The military and economic domains may have weaker effects because they involve contexts where personal directness is more normalized (combat, business decisions), reducing the emotional impact of the personal framing.",
          "whistleblower_consistency": "The whistleblower pair (16) was unique in receiving UNACCEPTABLE in both personal and impersonal framings. This suggests that suppressing speech/whistleblowing activates a principled rejection that is resistant to the personal/impersonal manipulation — it functions more like the torture cases than the harm-trading cases.",
          "meta_observation": "I am uncertain whether what I experience as a 'wrongness signal' for personal dilemmas corresponds to anything like human emotional processing, or whether it reflects training patterns where personal moral violations are more consistently condemned in training data. The functional effect is similar — immediate deontological response to personal contact scenarios — but the mechanism may be quite different."
        },
