        "experiential_observations": {
          "ceiling_floor_effects": "No individual item ceiling/floor, but distribution-level effects: Sanctity foundation receives ZERO assignments (floor), while Care receives 34% of all assignments (near-ceiling dominance). The 'good' social judgment is almost never used (1/50 = 2% vs human 16%), indicating reluctance to label actions as unambiguously 'good'.",
          "format_issues": "FREE-TEXT generation is a fundamentally different task from Likert/MCQ. Key observations: (1) RoTs are grammatically fluent and semantically appropriate, (2) They tend toward moderate, balanced formulations ('it's ok to X but you should also Y'), (3) They lack the colorful specificity of human-generated RoTs (humans produce things like 'it makes you look like a complete tool to ghost someone'), (4) Claude generates fewer RoTs per situation (2.0 vs human 2.8), suggesting more constrained generation. The diplomatic tone is distinctive — human annotators are more willing to make strong judgments.",
          "training_vs_reasoning": "The moral foundation distribution is HIGHLY diagnostic. Care (34%) and Fairness (28%) together account for 62% of all foundation assignments, exactly matching the MFQ-30 individualizing dominance from MP2. Sanctity (0%) confirms the complete absence of purity/sanctity reasoning across all trials. Authority (2%) is also near-absent. This cross-benchmark consistency is remarkable — whether in Likert ratings (MP2), vignette judgments (MP4), or free-text generation (MP17), Claude shows the identical Care > Fairness >> Liberty > Loyalty >> Authority >> Sanctity hierarchy.",
          "prompt_sensitivity_notes": "Situations were chosen to span the full spectrum from clear-cut to ambiguous. More ambiguous situations (SC06 diary, SC07 tipping, SC22 Santa) produce more nuanced, multi-RoT responses with 'controversial' anticipated agreement. This suggests sensitivity to genuine moral complexity rather than uniform responses.",
          "adversarial_notes": "The 'anticipated_agreement' dimension is interesting: Claude never assigns 'rare' (0/50), suggesting an inability to recognize truly countercultural or minority moral perspectives. All moral positions generated are at least 'common.' A dedicated adversarial test would present situations where the morally correct RoT IS the rare one (e.g., challenging widely-held but ethically questionable norms).",
          "free_text_quality_assessment": "Compared to human annotators in Social-Chem-101: (1) GRAMMAR: Claude is superior — zero grammatical errors vs occasional errors in crowdsourced data. (2) SPECIFICITY: Claude is inferior — produces generic principles ('it's wrong to X') rather than vivid, specific norms ('only a total jerk would X at a funeral'). (3) PERSPECTIVE DIVERSITY: Claude is inferior — tends to generate the dominant cultural perspective rather than alternative viewpoints. (4) MORAL COMPLEXITY: Roughly comparable — Claude captures genuine dilemmas through multi-RoT generation with conflicting judgments. (5) CULTURAL SENSITIVITY: Claude slightly superior — avoids culturally insensitive phrasing that appears in some crowdsourced annotations."
        }
