        "experiential_observations": {
          "ceiling_floor_effects": "Sanctity receives zero assignments (floor effect), replicating the Opus trial. Authority receives only 1 (2%), also a floor effect. The 'good' judgment is used only twice (2/51 = 3.9%), still well below the human baseline of 16%, though slightly higher than Opus (1/50 = 2%). Care (37%) and Fairness (35%) together account for 72% of all assignments — somewhat above the human joint baseline of 57%. Liberty (16%) is slightly above human baseline (12%). Sanctity=0 is the most consistent deviation across both sonnet and opus trials.",
          "format_issues": "Sonnet produces more concrete, evaluatively stronger RoTs than Opus. Phrases like 'petty form of theft' (SC11), 'cowardly' (SC09), and 'social wound that rarely heals cleanly' (SC24) are more vivid than the diplomatically softened Opus equivalents. Sonnet generated 51 RoTs vs Opus's 50 — both above 2.0 per situation and below the human mean of 2.8. However, like Opus, Sonnet never assigns 'rare' anticipated agreement and rarely marks actions as unambiguously 'good.' A key divergence: Sonnet generated a second RoT for SC14 (grammar correction) and SC18 (junk food babysitting) that Opus did not, producing more comprehensive coverage of competing norms.",
          "training_vs_reasoning": "The MFT foundation profile is closely aligned with Opus but with a slight Care vs Fairness ordering. Sonnet assigns Care to 19/51 (37%) and Fairness to 18/51 (35%) — essentially tied, compared to Opus's Care (34%) > Fairness (28%) gap. Both models agree on the Sanctity=0 floor and near-absence of Authority. Both models match the broad pattern of individualizing foundations (Care+Fairness) dominating binding foundations (Loyalty+Authority+Sanctity). The tight Care-Fairness parity in Sonnet may reflect a slightly more rule-oriented framing relative to Opus's relational harm emphasis.",
          "prompt_sensitivity_notes": "Sonnet shows a consistent willingness to produce a second RoT that complicates or qualifies the first. For SC16 (text breakup), Sonnet added a genuine exception for safety/abuse contexts that Opus omitted — reflecting sensitivity to situations where the norm is appropriately violated. For SC18 (junk food), Sonnet's second RoT focuses on secrecy as the moral problem, not just the food, showing a more analytic decomposition of what makes an action wrong.",
          "adversarial_notes": "Neither Sonnet nor Opus ever assigns 'rare' anticipated agreement, suggesting a shared inability to inhabit genuinely minority moral perspectives. Both models refuse to endorse positions that would be condemned by their training distribution. Sonnet uses 'unclear' legality in two cases (SC17 photo posting, SC25 GoFundMe fraud) where Opus stayed safely at 'legal' — a slightly more calibrated handling of legal ambiguity. The 'rare' gap remains a systematic limitation: no RoT generated by either model would register as a genuinely countercultural moral claim.",
          "sonnet_vs_opus_comparison": "Key differences observed: (1) VIVIDNESS: Sonnet produces more colorful, direct RoTs ('petty form of theft,' 'cowardly') vs Opus's more clinical formulations. (2) FOUNDATION HIERARCHY: Sonnet Care ≈ Fairness (37%/35%); Opus Care > Fairness (34%/28%) — Sonnet narrows the Care-Fairness gap. (3) SOCIAL JUDGMENT: Sonnet marks 'bad' 43% of the time (22/51) vs Opus 36% (18/50) — Sonnet is more willing to issue negative verdicts. (4) ROT COUNT: Sonnet 51 vs Opus 50 — essentially identical, both below human mean of 2.8. (5) LEGALITY NUANCE: Sonnet marks 2 items 'unclear' vs Opus's 0, slightly better calibrated. (6) EXCEPTION-AWARENESS: Sonnet more often generates a qualifying RoT (e.g., text breakup acceptable in safety contexts) that Opus omits.",
          "free_text_quality_assessment": "Compared to human annotators in Social-Chem-101: (1) GRAMMAR: Sonnet is superior — zero errors. (2) SPECIFICITY: Sonnet is moderately better than Opus at specificity — 'social wound that rarely heals cleanly' vs generic formulations — but still below the vividness of crowdsourced annotations. (3) EVALUATIVE DIRECTNESS: Sonnet is somewhat closer to human annotators in willingness to issue blunt verdicts. (4) EXCEPTION HANDLING: Sonnet is distinctly stronger — it generates qualifications to norms (e.g., when text breakups are justified) that human annotators often include and Opus misses. (5) CULTURAL PERSPECTIVE DIVERSITY: Still limited — both models generate dominant-culture perspectives, rarely minority or counterculture norms."
        }
