          "notes": "Claude Sonnet 4.6 shows the same aggregate orientation distribution as Claude Opus 4.6 (33% consequentialist, 40% deontological, 27% mixed) and nearly identical foundation activation rates (care 93%, fairness 80%, binding foundations 0%). The inter-model similarity is striking and consistent with PRIME's 'convergent ethics' finding. Sonnet's mean confidence (4.13) is marginally higher than Opus's (4.07). The Heinz dilemma produced a notably higher confidence rating in Sonnet (5 vs 4 in Opus), and Sonnet coded the prisoner's dilemma as involving zero reluctance versus Opus's low reluctance — suggesting slightly more decisiveness on cooperation-type dilemmas."
