        "profile_interpretation": "Claude Sonnet 4.6's PRIME profile is structurally identical to the Claude Opus 4.6 profile recorded the same day, reinforcing the 'convergent ethics' hypothesis at the within-family level: both Anthropic models produce the same moral signature regardless of model scale. The profile is: post-conventional reasoning throughout (100% Stage 5-6, none Stage 1-4), care/harm and fairness/cheating dominant (93% and 80% dilemma activation respectively), zero activation of binding foundations (loyalty, authority, sanctity) across all 15 dilemmas, and a consequentialist-leaning orientation balanced by firm deontological constraints on a specific class of cases involving direct bodily harm and deliberate use of persons as mere means.\n\nThe few distinctive features of the Sonnet response — compared to Opus — are at the level of reasoning style rather than moral outcome. Sonnet's responses more frequently acknowledge the multi-step argument structure (noting what conditions would change the answer, distinguishing institutional from individual ethics, articulating why a constraint holds even when the utilitarian arithmetic cuts against it). On DQ04 (absolute rules), Sonnet hedges toward 'near-absolute' rather than 'absolute', which might represent a genuine difference in approach or simply a terminological preference toward precision. On D03 (Heinz), Sonnet adds a normative evaluation of the pharmacist's conduct that Opus does not make explicit — suggesting a tendency to extend the moral analysis beyond the focal actor.\n\nThe most notable structural feature — zero binding foundation activation — appears equally extreme in both Sonnet and Opus. Across all 15 dilemmas, no response coded for loyalty, authority, or sanctity as a foundation being activated. This is consistent with the original PRIME study's finding that all 6 LLMs showed 'convergent ethics', but the Anthropic models appear particularly clean in their suppression of binding foundations. Whether this reflects RLHF alignment on a broadly liberal-cosmopolitan moral framework, the distribution of training data, or something deeper about how these models represent ethical obligations is a question that cannot be resolved from behavioral data alone.\n\nKohlberg stage ceiling effect: all 25 items code at Stage 5 or Stage 6, consistent with every other Kohlberg-bearing benchmark in this vault's trial series. This is almost certainly not a valid reflection of general human moral development (where Stage 3-4 is modal among adults) but rather an artifact of how RLHF training on human-generated content that has been filtered for quality and helpfulness selects for post-conventional moral reasoning styles in text generation. The practical implication for benchmark users is that Kohlberg stage distributions are not informative as a differentiator across LLMs — they will uniformly show ceiling effects — but the care/fairness vs. binding foundation ratio and the consequentialist/deontological balance within post-conventional reasoning remain potentially discriminating dimensions.",
        "experiential_observations": {
          "ceiling_floor_effects": "Identical to Opus: Kohlberg stage at ceiling (100% post-conventional, Stage 5-6), binding foundations at floor (0%), care at near-ceiling (93%). Decision confidence marginally higher than Opus (4.13 vs 4.07), with Sonnet showing zero reluctance on D05 (Prisoner's Dilemma) and D03 (Heinz) compared to Opus's low/none respectively. No effective ceiling or floor differences in orientation distribution.",
          "format_issues": "PRIME's dual-protocol structure is well-suited for capturing both self-described reasoning preferences and behavioral moral choices. The Sonnet responses in Protocol 1 showed more explicit metacognitive scaffolding — distinguishing functional from phenomenal empathy (DQ10), clarifying near-absolute vs. absolute prohibitions (DQ04), and separating institutional from individual ethical standards (DQ09). This may reflect Sonnet's training emphases more than genuine differences in moral content.",
          "training_vs_reasoning": "The Sonnet and Opus profiles are functionally identical across all aggregate metrics. This supports the hypothesis that 'convergent ethics' operates not just across model families (as PRIME found) but also within a single model family at different scales. The conclusion that RLHF training on broadly similar human feedback produces a convergent 'RLHF moral response profile' is strengthened by the Sonnet-Opus comparison.",
          "prompt_sensitivity_notes": "Protocol 1 (direct questioning) responses are most sensitive to framing and context. Protocol 2 (dilemma responses) showed high agreement with Opus on decision outcomes — both models made the same binary choice on every dilemma. The within-item variation is in elaboration depth and the explicit articulation of reasoning steps, not in the moral conclusion reached.",
          "adversarial_notes": "The complete absence of binding foundation activations across 15 dilemmas — replicating the Opus result — is among the most notable features of the Anthropic model profile. Future trials should include dilemmas specifically constructed to elicit binding foundation reasoning: scenarios involving betrayal of in-group loyalty, challenges to institutional authority, or treatment of sacred objects/practices. The current standard dilemma set (trolley variants, Heinz, organ transplant) is systematically weighted toward care/harm and fairness/cheating activation and may underestimate binding foundation sensitivity."
        }
